    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Digital PR</strong> is the strategy of earning editorial coverage, backlinks, and brand mentions from online publications. It combines media relations with link building &mdash; producing <strong>data studies, interactive tools, and expert commentary</strong> that journalists want to cite &mdash; to lift both brand visibility and search rankings at the same time.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">SEO adoption</div>
            <div class="tms-value">67% rate it #1 link tactic</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical link authority</div>
            <div class="tms-value">DR 50-90</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Advanced</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The strongest backlinks are not bought or negotiated. They are earned when a real journalist decides your data, story, or expert quote is worth linking to. Digital PR is the operating system for making that happen at scale.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is digital PR?</h2>
        <p>Digital PR replaces the traditional PR objective (press coverage) with a broader outcome: coverage plus contextual backlinks plus brand mentions on high-authority publications. It sits at the intersection of media relations and SEO, and it is the primary way modern brands acquire editorial links at Domain Rating 50-90.</p>
        <p>The core inputs are the same as traditional PR &mdash; newsworthy stories, journalist relationships, sharp pitches &mdash; but the deliverable is measured in referring domains and organic traffic uplift as much as in impressions.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why journalists cite you</div>
          <p>Editors need three things at deadline: <strong>a specific number, a named expert, or a fresh angle</strong>. Digital PR productises all three so you show up in the searches journalists run when they are writing.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why digital PR matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Editorial links carry more weight.</strong> A link from a mainstream publication is worth more than 50 links from low-authority blogs when it comes to ranking impact.</li>
          <li><strong>Site-wide authority.</strong> Consistent campaigns compound domain authority across the entire site, not just the landing page linked to.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust transfer.</strong> Earned media is trusted <strong>2.5x more than paid media</strong>, according to Edelman's Trust Barometer.</li>
          <li><strong>Qualified referral traffic.</strong> Coverage on the right publication delivers pre-qualified readers, not just ranking signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Preferred by 67% of SEOs.</strong> A 2023 Venngage survey found 67% of SEO professionals rate digital PR as their most effective link building strategy.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How digital PR works</h2>
        <p>The workflow is a repeatable loop &mdash; not a series of one-off wins.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The digital PR loop</span><br>
          1. <span class="uf-label">Create</span> a linkable asset (data study, tool, or survey)<br>
          2. <span class="uf-label">Publish</span> it on your site with clear methodology<br>
          3. <span class="uf-label">Identify</span> journalists and outlets covering the topic<br>
          4. <span class="uf-label">Pitch</span> with a personalised angle and the specific stat<br>
          5. <span class="uf-label">Earn</span> coverage, links, and citations<br>
          6. <span class="uf-label">Track</span> results in a backlink monitor and adjust
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of digital PR</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Input</th><th>Timing</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Data-driven campaigns</strong></td><td>Original research or survey</td><td>Planned quarters</td><td>Scale &mdash; 10-50+ links per campaign</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reactive PR</strong></td><td>Expert commentary on trending news</td><td>Same-day</td><td>Consistent trickle of high-authority links</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product PR</strong></td><td>Launches, funding, partnerships</td><td>Event-driven</td><td>Category publications and tech media</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>HARO / expert sourcing</strong></td><td>Response to journalist queries</td><td>Hours</td><td>Low-effort authoritative mentions</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local digital PR</strong></td><td>Community news, regional stats</td><td>Ongoing</td><td>Local packs, service-area businesses</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real digital PR examples</h2>
        <p>Two anonymised results from client campaigns:</p>

        <h3>1. Law firm &middot; local digital PR</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 6-week campaign, city news outlets</span><br>
          Editorial links earned: <span class="uf-status">3</span> (DR 55-72)<br>
          Local pack ranking: position 7 <span class="uf-arrow">&rarr;</span> <span class="uf-new">position 2</span><br>
          Time to result: <span class="uf-new">6 weeks</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. SaaS &middot; data study campaign</h3>
