          Referring domains: <span class="uf-new">+38 unique</span><br>
          Domain Rating: 42 <span class="uf-arrow">&rarr;</span> <span class="uf-new">51</span><br>
          Organic traffic: <span class="uf-new">+34%</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Digital PR vs traditional link building</h2>
        <p>Both aim to acquire backlinks, but they operate on different rails.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Digital PR</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Editorial links from DR 50-90 publications</li>
              <li>Scales through single campaigns (10-50+ links)</li>
              <li>Adds brand credibility, not just link equity</li>
              <li>Journalist relationships compound over time</li>
              <li>Higher cost per campaign, higher unit value</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Traditional link building</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>One-at-a-time outreach (guest posts, resource pages)</li>
              <li>Quality varies widely across targets</li>
              <li>Cheaper per link, more manual effort</li>
              <li>Rarely produces top-tier publication links</li>
              <li>Complementary to PR, not a substitute</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 digital PR best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with data, not brand.</strong> Journalists cite specific numbers. "Our study of 3,000 respondents found..." beats "Our platform helps..."</li>
          <li><strong>Publish the asset before pitching.</strong> The link needs a destination. Host the study on your site with methodology and dataset.</li>
          <li><strong>Build journalist relationships in advance.</strong> Follow, comment, and be useful before you need the coverage.</li>
          <li><strong>Use local angles.</strong> National data broken down by city gives you 20+ regional angles from a single study.</li>
          <li><strong>Integrate with content publishing.</strong> Every campaign should tie back to a topic cluster you rank for.</li>
          <li><strong>Track referring domains, not just impressions.</strong> The SEO value is in unique linking domains, not media impressions.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake &mdash; pitching before the asset exists</div>
          <p>The fastest way to burn a journalist relationship is to pitch an idea with no landing page ready. Publish the study first, then pitch the specific stat with a direct link to the methodology. If a reporter has to email you back for the source, you have already lost the placement.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common digital PR mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mass-generic outreach</strong> &mdash; unpersonalised pitches get deleted or spam-reported.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing DR at any cost</strong> &mdash; a link on a huge site that has nothing to do with your niche is worth less than a DR 40 link in your category.</li>
          <li><strong>No-follow blindness</strong> &mdash; some huge publications no-follow all outbound links; measure brand + traffic, not just link equity.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring HARO</strong> &mdash; the highest ROI channel for small teams gets overlooked.</li>
          <li><strong>One-shot campaigns</strong> &mdash; single wins don't compound; the results come from 6-12 months of consistent output.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc pairs your organic content program with a digital PR arm &mdash; identifying linkable assets from your existing content, producing data-driven landing pages, and coordinating reactive commentary. You get compounding authority from search plus a steady drip of high-DR editorial links.</p>

